Pinterest, Press-- lot of Ps--

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:45.830
Press, "New York Times,"
Expedia, Flipboard, and Ted.

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:48.090
So those are the 11 apps
in that collection.

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:50.630
So the first of these
is Pattrn.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:56.000
So Pattrn is basically an app
that lets you look at

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:56.660
different wallpapers.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:59.970
And actually, these wallpapers
are all pattern tiles, hence

00:03:59.970 --> 00:04:01.260
the name Pattrn.

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:02.450
So they kind of tile across.

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:05.330
They're not just one big photo
or anything like that.

00:04:05.330 --> 00:04:07.910
But it's really something that
lets you browse and browse

00:04:07.910 --> 00:04:09.750
patterned wallpapers
and set them.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:12.580
So we're only looking
at tablet today.

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:15.010
One of the key things in this
collection, actually, before

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:19.110
we jump in here, is that most,
if not all, of these apps are

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:21.640
really responsibly designed.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:23.000
So this is one of the--

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.390
meaning it works on tablet, it
works on phone, it works on

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:27.300
seven-inch, and so on.

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:32.290
And so this app right now is one
of the best examples of a

00:04:32.290 --> 00:04:35.260
very nice standardish responsive
design, where

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:39.280
basically on a tablet here, you
see multiple columns of

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:40.860
patterns, of wallpapers.

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.200
And on a phone, you actually see
fewer columns, maybe just

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:46.050
one column and two columns
on landscape.

00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:49.940
And then you have your kind of
core navigation on the left.

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:52.660
You basically can jump in
between or switch between

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:54.500
different sections.

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:57.600
And then you can open up one
of these wallpapers.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:00.210
And one of the nice touches is
that they have these very

00:05:00.210 --> 00:05:03.070
subtle animations here that
let you see more.

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:05.720
And actually, it also goes
into lights-out mode.

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:10.770
So you actually fade out, or you
dim the navigation bar and

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:12.830
the status bar in the process.

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:15.610
And one of the last things I
wanted to mention about this

00:05:15.610 --> 00:05:17.600
app-- and obviously the
responsive design, I think for

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:19.460
me, is one of the biggest
things about it

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:20.500
that makes it so great--

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:22.920
one of the last things is that
there are subtle little

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:26.490
touches here and there, like
letting you rotate the

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:30.090
wallpaper, set the wallpaper
automatically on a schedule.

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:33.000
And then also, just the overall
fit and finish, it

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.480
really does feel like
a really, truly

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:39.730
Android-designed app.

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:42.380
So overall, just a
very solid app.

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:44.356
That's the first one
in our collection.

00:05:44.356 --> 00:05:45.700
Can we move on Pinterest?

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:46.460
ADAM KOCH: All right.

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:49.290
So let's talk a little
bit about Pinterest.

00:05:49.290 --> 00:05:52.050
So for those of you who are not
familiar with Pinterest,

00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:54.800
it's a social networking app
that sort of revolves around

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:57.920
these virtual pinboards,
where you can

00:05:57.920 --> 00:05:59.680
pin up virtual content.

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:03.420
I will admit I am not a big
Pinterest user myself.

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:05.590
But that doesn't mean I can't
play with the app and use the

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:08.380
app and see how it's beautifully
designed.

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:10.230
So the first thing you'll
notice, and this is kind of

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:13.610
interesting because there's no
sort of standard action bar.

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:15.450
And of course, if you've
listened to any of our shows,

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:18.056
we're always talking action bar,
action bar, action bar.

00:06:18.056 --> 00:06:21.110
But in this case, they've
actually gone for almost like

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:24.700
a hybrid between top-level tabs,
which you may see in an

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:27.640
app like, say, the "People" app,
and the sort of standard

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:30.870
action bar, where you have
branding only in the top left.

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:35.190
And it actually works nicely
because on their website, they

00:06:35.190 --> 00:06:37.640
have this same design
and layout.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.880
So you can see here, they've
still got the sort of standard

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:45.200
interaction patterns of swiping
between these tabs,

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:47.650
where the middle tab is
really sort of home

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:49.650
or browse your stream.

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:52.180
And the left tab, while it does
have a search icon, it's

00:06:52.180 --> 00:06:57.060
more of a discover tab or
something along those lines.

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:01.090
And so that's the first
I wanted to call out.

00:07:01.090 --> 00:07:03.650
The second thing is this
multi-column layout.

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:07.070
And that's, again, very similar
to their website.

00:07:07.070 --> 00:07:09.810
And this is really nice because,
obviously, their

00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:11.760
social network revolves heavily
around content, so

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:13.760
it's a very content-forward
design.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:16.140
And it has the added advantage
that it's also very

00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:16.810
responsive.

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:19.810
It scales very well to different
screen sizes.

00:07:19.810 --> 00:07:21.800
As we mentioned before, we
couldn't show you the phone

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:22.530
layout today.

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:25.670
But you'll see on the phone
layout and on the smaller

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:29.310
tablet or portrait layouts,
you'll see that it reduces the

00:07:29.310 --> 00:07:32.030
number of columns
nicely there.

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:33.320
ROMAN NURIK: One of the best
things about this, really

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:37.320
quick, is that the Chrome of the
app, the bar at the top, I

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:42.000
guess the action/tab bar, the
bar at the top follows the

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.250
natural Android interaction
model, but the content is very

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:46.010
much Pinterest.

00:07:46.010 --> 00:07:47.130
It's very much

00:07:47.130 --> 00:07:48.740
Pinterest-branded content, almost.

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:52.850
The exact layout of
the posts is very

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:54.010
much a Pinterest thing.

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:55.967
So that's one of the
ways in which they

00:07:55.967 --> 00:07:57.060
let their brand show.

00:07:57.060 --> 00:07:59.490
ADAM KOCH: And they've also
sort of fused their brand

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:01.420
design with the Holo
design language.

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:03.875
So you sort of see the
Holo design tabs.

00:08:03.875 --> 00:08:08.520
You sort of see the buttons
are much flatter than what

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:11.000
they have on their website
and in other platforms.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.520
They have sort of the
overflow down here.

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:15.560
So they've done a very good
job at the middle ground

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:19.810
between fusing Android design
with their own brand.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:20.970
NICK BUTCHER: And just one
little thing on Pinterest.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:23.950
I absolutely love the way, as
it's loading in a new image,

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:27.076
it'll take the average color
of the image, right?

00:08:27.076 --> 00:08:28.350
Yeah, there we go.

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:31.780
So the color shown will be the
average color of the image

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:32.330
once it's loaded.

00:08:32.330 --> 00:08:35.640
It's a completely unnecessary
detail that I love.

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:36.439
It is delightful.

00:08:36.439 --> 00:08:39.309
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, it's one
extra database field, but for

00:08:39.309 --> 00:08:42.795
a lot more value there.

00:08:42.795 --> 00:08:43.830
ADAM KOCH: All right, guys.

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:44.450
So that's Pinterest.

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:47.010
We really like the
Pinterest app.

00:08:47.010 --> 00:08:47.570
ROMAN NURIK: Pocket?

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:49.385
Nick, you want to talk
about Pocket?

00:08:49.385 --> 00:08:51.010
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah,
absolutely.

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:53.725
So Pocket, hopefully you know,
is kind of a catch-up reading

00:08:53.725 --> 00:08:55.640
of the news sites.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.730
So you can save sites, videos,
images, and so forth into your

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:00.990
Pocket and catch up later.

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:02.990
So when trying to pick what I
wanted to highlight in this

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:05.050
application, I initially
thought about

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:06.000
the responsive design.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:07.520
Because like these other
applications we looked at so

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:10.370
far, this app responds
beautifully to the form factor

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:11.890
of the device you're
looking at it on.

00:09:11.890 --> 00:09:14.980
So on a phone, for example,
it'll use list-based

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:17.480
navigation when you click
a [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:19.720
And as you get to larger
devices, it breaks out into a

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:22.590
grid, and then there's kind
of an asymmetric grid,

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:23.770
as you can see here.

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:25.260
If you have more content, there
would be lots and lots

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:25.530
at the top.

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:27.341
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, sorry about
not filling it out completely.

00:09:27.341 --> 00:09:29.025
ADAM KOCH: I forgot to add
it in, but that's OK.

00:09:29.025 --> 00:09:29.450
NICK BUTCHER: No problem.

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:32.400
But in fact, my favorite detail,
I think, about this

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:37.180
application is the sheer focus
on the reading experience.

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:41.010
The application does a lot of
stuff, but it doesn't feel

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:43.180
heavy in its user interface.

00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:45.830
Everything seems to get out of
the way in order to let you

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:48.110
have the best reading
experience.

00:09:48.110 --> 00:09:50.810
So for example, the user
interface here, the action bar

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:52.360
and so forth, is all
quite muted.

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:54.280
So it immediately recedes
out of the way.

00:09:54.280 --> 00:09:56.305
And if you could start scrolling
down through the

00:09:56.305 --> 00:09:58.884
article, as soon as you start
scrolling-- that's a very

00:09:58.884 --> 00:09:59.362
short article.

00:09:59.362 --> 00:10:02.360
Were it longer, as soon as you
start scrolling down, the

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:03.540
action bar hides.

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:06.700
And once again, we go into
this, what we refer to as

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:10.130
lights out mode, where
the system bar and

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:11.275
navigation bar recede.

00:10:11.275 --> 00:10:14.260
See the slightly dim state.

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:16.750
So it's all about the
reading experience.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:18.950
But as soon as you start
scrolling back up, which

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:21.510
indicates you've finished the
article, for example, the

00:10:21.510 --> 00:10:23.280
affordances jump right back.

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:26.380
So you can check the time or
multitask to another app or

00:10:26.380 --> 00:10:28.090
use one of the action
bar options.

00:10:28.090 --> 00:10:31.230
So it just gets out of your
way, and it just works.

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:33.910
And I love that focus on
the reading experience.

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:35.060
And the same thing's
true of their kind

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:35.960
of pagination model.

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:38.420
So you can either read it in
an endless stream, so where

00:10:38.420 --> 00:10:39.640
you're swiping up and down.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:43.660
Or you can swipe left and right
to change to a paginated

00:10:43.660 --> 00:10:44.610
content model.

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:47.600
And I love the fact that there's
no-- you can imagine

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:49.640
that one way of implementing
that interface would be some

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:52.450
kind of toggle or switch or
machinery in order to do it.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:54.810
But instead of doing that, they
just listen to how you're

00:10:54.810 --> 00:10:55.520
trying to use it.

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:59.370
So if you scroll vertically,
then it'll give you a vertical

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:00.770
stream of content.

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:02.880
And if you scroll horizontally,
then it'll

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:05.780
automatically flip into this
paginated content model.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:08.540
So again, it just reduces all
the machinery around it and

00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:10.860
just really, really focuses on
getting out of your way and

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:12.070
letting you get to
the content.

00:11:12.070 --> 00:11:13.730
So really, really great
attention to

00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:16.210
detail in this app.

00:11:16.210 --> 00:11:18.782
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, I'd say
that it's one of the best

00:11:18.782 --> 00:11:21.820
in-reading experiences.

00:11:21.820 --> 00:11:25.450
If at all, you need to build
an app that lets you read

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:28.390
through large chunks of content
that have large body

00:11:28.390 --> 00:11:32.400
